00:02:55.020 --> 00:03:01.100
be one of two things, either we are going
to talk right pass each other or we can find

00:03:01.100 --> 00:03:07.190
a synthesis where we benefit from the best
of each other's thinkings. I like to think

00:03:07.190 --> 00:03:15.550
that that is what we are going to do today.
The third thing about myself is that I think

00:03:15.550 --> 00:03:25.270
of it sometimes as a cosmic joke that I should
be writing a book about data. Because of a

00:03:25.270 --> 00:03:29.820
gruesome incident that I will not go into
detail, about a 7th and 8th grade algebra

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:36.740
teacher who didn't know how to deal with people
with ADD left me permanently scared when it

00:03:36.740 --> 00:03:43.319
came to dealing with data. So, for the longest
time, as far as I was concerned there was

00:03:43.319 --> 00:03:49.349
only one reason to deal with data. And that
was to go over the Red Sox batting averages.

00:03:49.349 --> 00:03:59.390
Look what that got us. Eventually I did come
around and became convinced of the value of

00:03:59.390 --> 00:04:05.150
data. And when I became convinced of that
value of data, I found it really difficult

00:04:05.150 --> 00:04:13.040
to get hold of it. For the longest time that
was very legitimate. It was costly, difficult,

00:04:13.040 --> 00:04:19.489
a lot of technological barriers to gathering,
processing, and disseminating data. But as

00:04:19.489 --> 00:04:24.770
you and I know, those have all been taken
care of and yet this mind set still remains.

00:04:24.770 --> 00:04:31.259
It’s very much, as far as I'm concerned,
like that last scene in Raiders of the Lost

00:04:31.259 --> 00:04:37.699
Ark. Where the Ark was boxed up in a crate
and put in a government warehouse. And you

00:04:37.699 --> 00:04:48.639
knew that it was never going to be accessed
again. And it seems to me that when you substitute

00:04:48.639 --> 00:04:58.539
data warehouse, it’s such a wonderful term.
In its symbolic aspects that, unfortunately,

00:04:58.539 --> 00:05:02.120
often stuff gets into the data warehouse and
we never see it again.

00:05:02.120 --> 00:05:10.029
But I maintain that time has come to end that
practice and that it is time for data for

00:05:10.029 --> 00:05:16.860
the rest of us. The time has come to liberate
data. Liberating data makes it automatically

00:05:16.860 --> 00:05:23.729
available for all who need it, when and where
they need it, in forms to use and with freedom

00:05:23.729 --> 00:05:31.599
to use as they choose, while at the same time
protecting privacy and security. And I maintain

00:05:31.599 --> 00:05:39.639
that this is really crucial for a lot of today’s
challenges. I think that the whole concept

00:05:39.639 --> 00:05:45.410
of liberating data is crucial to deal with
some of the issues we are facing today. First

00:05:45.410 --> 00:05:51.059
of all, within the corporate workplace, if
you give people real time data for the first

00:05:51.059 --> 00:05:59.080
time ever. In the past we have had a situation
where that has been primarily limited to senior

00:05:59.080 --> 00:06:04.789
executives and elites in areas like marketing
and things like that due to do the costs of

00:06:04.789 --> 00:06:12.409
DI dashboards and other barriers of that sort.
When you start giving people access to real

00:06:12.409 --> 00:06:19.541
time data they can really use, you are going
to get better decision making, particularly

00:06:19.541 --> 00:06:25.479
if you add in social media tools to be able
to collaboratively analyze and act on that

00:06:25.479 --> 00:06:29.249
data. I think you are going to get fundamentally
better decision making because you are going

00:06:29.249 --> 00:06:33.962
to get a number of different perspectives
brought to bear on it. Secondly, you are going

00:06:33.962 --> 00:06:39.430
to be able to automate a lot of processes
that have been manual in the past. That certainly

00:06:39.430 --> 00:06:45.809
has economic benefits to it. Thirdly, one
of the big demands of the republicans in the

00:06:45.809 --> 00:06:53.849
US. I did a lecture in Montreal on a related
subject this week with an international audience.

00:06:53.849 --> 00:07:00.520
And I was saying to them that this is equally
applicable on worldwide basis. But focusing

00:07:00.520 --> 00:07:05.830
just in the US right now, one of the concerns
with the GOP is cutting the cost of government

00:07:05.830 --> 00:07:13.319
regulations. There is a tremendous potential
when you have seamless flow of data to cut

00:07:13.319 --> 00:07:20.580
the cost of regulatory reporting. And at the
same time, this is somewhat paradoxical. The

00:07:20.580 --> 00:07:25.520
experiences in Australia and the Netherlands,
the two places that have really done this

00:07:25.520 --> 00:07:31.440
to the greatest extent. They've actually been
capable of improving the quality of regulation.

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:35.909
And that’s because of the fact that for
the first time ever when companies file a

00:07:35.909 --> 00:07:42.360
single unified data file that goes to the
central government and then automatically

00:07:42.360 --> 00:07:48.830
flows into all of the different agencies,
for the first time ever all those agencies

00:07:48.830 --> 00:07:56.349
can survey a given company at the same time.
And equally important, and I think this is

00:07:56.349 --> 00:08:03.919
true both within the business sector. I would
argue that banks, probably more than any other

00:08:03.919 --> 00:08:08.479
sector of the economy would benefit from this.
Because I don't know about you, but frankly

00:08:08.479 --> 00:08:15.770
I don't trust any bank anymore. And the only
way they are going to earn my trust is through

00:08:15.770 --> 00:08:24.919
transparency. There is actually a professor
who I finally met in this conference in Montreal

00:08:24.919 --> 00:08:33.250
who was saying that, had a system of the sort
I'm talking about been in effect in the mid-2000s

00:08:33.250 --> 00:08:42.580
we actually might have totally avoided all
the bank shenanigans and the whole economic

00:08:42.580 --> 00:08:48.740
collapse never would have happened. Can you
imagine that? That is rather damning. And

00:08:48.740 --> 00:08:56.230
finally, so that you can restore this through
transparency and earn the public trust. And

00:08:56.230 --> 00:09:03.509
finally, probably on a most imaginative stand
point, you can also make the public partners

00:09:03.509 --> 00:09:12.620
and crowdsource a lot of innovation. Now how
would you actually go about doing this? In

00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:18.810
the book I outline a five step process that
starts with making the organization truly

00:09:18.810 --> 00:09:27.649
data centric. I mean that almost as much literally
as figuratively. That thinking of, in a very

00:09:27.649 --> 00:09:35.970
systemic way, on your date flow coming from
the center of the corporation. No matter where

00:09:35.970 --> 00:09:42.460
it is housed but coming from the center and
they flowing through massive feedback loops,

00:09:42.460 --> 00:09:49.490
coming back in again, so you have this continuous
flow of data. Secondly, and I can’t emphasize

00:09:49.490 --> 00:09:57.240
this enough I’m going to call Google on
this to some extent also. The second step

00:09:57.240 --> 00:10:07.079
is tagging and syndicating data. The goal,
I’m convinced that we need to be pursuing

00:10:07.079 --> 00:10:16.350
is entering data one time, only one time.
That’s perfectly feasible now, with tagging

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:21.960
of data.&nbsp; Because all I have to do is enter
once and then repot those tags elsewhere and

00:10:21.960 --> 00:10:29.220
the date will automatically flow to those
places and the language that I’m particularly

00:10:29.220 --> 00:10:35.560
obsessed with right now is XBRL. The eXtensible
Business Reporting Language which from everything

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:42.779
I’ve been able to learn about Google until
now seems that even Google is not using.&nbsp;

00:10:42.779 --> 00:10:48.350
There is only a handful literally of companies
worldwide who are using the extensible business

00:10:48.350 --> 00:10:54.300
language reporting. Behind the firewall everybody
now is required to us it when they report

00:10:54.300 --> 00:11:01.589
to the SCC.&nbsp; But behind the firewall you
have literally five organizations in the whole

00:11:01.589 --> 00:11:08.279
world from the cutting edge change that are
realizing all sorts of incredible benefits.

00:11:08.279 --> 00:11:15.640
But Google is not one of them. So one of the
things you get is as benefit.&nbsp; When you start

00:11:15.640 --> 00:11:20.860
with this and you only enter the data once
is that you get a single version of the truth.

